## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates the ability to design a practical KCA workflow for ephemeral analytics workers. It covers bootstrap attestation, short TLS certificate lifetimes, SPIFFE identity binding, per-workload policy enforcement, and includes practical testing for certificate rotation and cross-region failover scenarios.

## Key Concepts
- Ephemeral worker provisioning
- SPIFFE identities and TLS enrollment
- Policy binding and renewal logic
- Auditing and offline revocation
- Failover and latency testing

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-config for worker enrollment
const workerConfig = {
  bootstrapService: 'https://bootstrap.<region>.example.com',
  kcaEndpoint: 'https://kca.example.com',
  spiffeIdTemplate: 'spiffe://example.com/worker/${WORKER_ID}',
  certTTL: 300,
  renewThreshold: 60,
  scopes: ['data-worker'],
  workloadPolicies: {
    'data-worker': ['read:analytics', 'write:analytics']
  }
};

// Worker enrollment flow
async function enrollWorker(workerId, region) {
  // 1. Attest to regional bootstrap service
  const attestation = await bootstrapService.attest(workerId, region);

  // 2. CSR-enroll to central KCA
  const cert = await kca.issueCertificate({
    csr: await generateCSR(workerConfig.spiffeIdTemplate, workerId),
    ttl: workerConfig.certTTL,
    spiffeId: `spiffe://example.com/worker/${workerId}`,
    scope: workerConfig.scopes[0],
    policies: workerConfig.workloadPolicies['data-worker']
  });

  return cert;
}

// Renewal on reconnect with exponential backoff
async function renewCertificate(cert, attempt = 1) {
  try {
    return await kca.renewCertificate(cert);
  } catch (err) {
    if (attempt < maxRetries) {
      await sleep(Math.min(1000 * 2 ** attempt, 30000));
      return renewCertificate(cert, attempt + 1);
    }
    throw err;
  }
}
```
